  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_505149241" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/505149241" />
    <a title="Derek Davis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1950709-derek-davis"><img alt="Derek Davis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1289699546p2/1950709.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/505149241?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek Davis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek Davis" href="/user/show/1950709-derek-davis">Derek Davis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer505149241" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4594370174501289925">Barker, in general, is a heck of a lot better writer than fellow horror icon Stephen King (except in King&apos;s short stories). He keeps his narrative together with a smooth action curve (even when there&apos;s little action) and restrains himself from having his characters add juvenile comments and sophomoric humor. <br/><br/>His &quot;hero&quot; here, Marty, a semi-parolee, is a nuanced character who learns as he goes, expanding his internal horizons even as the horror slowly mounts. Indeed, all the characters are full, c</span>
  <span id="freeText4594370174501289925" style="display:none">Barker, in general, is a heck of a lot better writer than fellow horror icon Stephen King (except in King's short stories). He keeps his narrative together with a smooth action curve (even when there's little action) and restrains himself from having his characters add juvenile comments and sophomoric humor. <br /><br />His "hero" here, Marty, a semi-parolee, is a nuanced character who learns as he goes, expanding his internal horizons even as the horror slowly mounts. Indeed, all the characters are full, contradictory human beings, with the chemical-industry titan, Whitehead, able to alternate convincingly between unleavened arrogance and small-minded fear. Even Mamoulian, the semi-supernatural villain, has sympathetic qualities.<br /><br />Barker also has an eye for the truly horrific image – a reanimated dog eating its own hindquarters – and delivers what may be the highest maggot-count in history without it seeming pointless verbal shoveling.<br /><br />So why not the fifth star? Because, unlike King, Barker maintains an authorial distance from his characters – as though watching a lab experiment unfold – that, at least to my mind, dampens the immediacy of the horror. You might well think otherwise.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4594370174501289925" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

