<div id="review_739588263" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/739588263" />
    <a title="Leon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24366758-leon"><img alt="Leon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380605024p2/24366758.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/739588263?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leon" href="/user/show/24366758-leon">Leon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer739588263" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1283540842841204884">What a smart, dazzling, gleefully obscene work of horror fiction! <br/><br/>I&apos;ve slowly grown bored with most contemporary &quot;literary&quot; novels, and so have been slumming it up with authors like Clive Barker -- his Books of Blood is so good I don&apos;t ever want it to end -- and Clark Ashton Smith. This stuff is just plain fun. In this novel, Barker manages to create interesting and mightily flawed characters who are described so well you&apos;d think they were autobiographical (Christ I hope not), and then puts them</span>
  <span id="freeText1283540842841204884" style="display:none">What a smart, dazzling, gleefully obscene work of horror fiction! <br /><br />I've slowly grown bored with most contemporary "literary" novels, and so have been slumming it up with authors like Clive Barker -- his Books of Blood is so good I don't ever want it to end -- and Clark Ashton Smith. This stuff is just plain fun. In this novel, Barker manages to create interesting and mightily flawed characters who are described so well you'd think they were autobiographical (Christ I hope not), and then puts them in the most INSANE gut-raveling situations imaginable. I swear, the last third of this book had some of the most riveting action I've read in a long time. (How a writer can make hallucinated shit-monsters emerging from a gaping toilet poetic is beyond me.) <br /><br />Barker writes gorgeous Grand Guignol set-pieces that make most of today's horror authors look mild.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1283540842841204884" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


